  "prompt": "What are the places to visit in Chennai?",
  "response": "Chennai, a vibrant city with a rich history and culture, offers a plethora of attractions for visitors. Here's a breakdown of popular places to visit, categorized for your convenience:\n\n**Historical & Cultural Sites:**\n\n*   **Fort St. George:** A historic British fortress, now housing the Tamil Nadu Legislative Assembly and a museum showcasing artifacts from the British era.\n*   **Government Museum:** One of the oldest museums in India, boasting a vast collection of artifacts, including bronze sculptures, archaeological finds, and numismatic items.\n*   **Kapaleeshwarar Temple:** A stunning Dravidian-style temple dedicated to Lord Shiva and Goddess Parvati, known for its intricate carvings and vibrant atmosphere. Located in Mylapore.\n*   **San Thome Basilica:** Built over the tomb of St. Thomas the Apostle, this Roman Catholic basilica is a significant pilgrimage site.\n*   **Valluvar Kottam:** A memorial dedicated to the classical Tamil poet Thiruvalluvar, featuring a chariot-shaped monument and inscriptions of his Thirukkural verses.\n*   **DakshinaChitra:** A living history museum showcasing the art, architecture, lifestyle, and performing arts of South India. Located a bit outside the city.\n*   **Fort Museum:** Housed within Fort St. George, this museum displays relics of the British Raj, including uniforms, weapons, and documents.\n*   **Ripon Building:** A magnificent example of Indo-Saracenic architecture, currently housing the Chennai Corporation. While you can't typically go inside, it's worth admiring from the outside.\n\n**Religious Sites (beyond Kapaleeshwarar & San Thome):**\n\n*   **Ashtalakshmi Temple:** A relatively modern temple dedicated to the eight forms of Goddess Lakshmi, situated on the Elliot's Beach.\n*   **Parthasarathy Temple:** A Vaishnavite temple dedicated to Lord Krishna, one of the oldest temples in Chennai.\n*   **St. Mary's Church:** The oldest Anglican church in India, located within Fort St. George.\n\n**Beaches & Waterfront:**\n\n*   **Marina Beach:** One of the longest urban beaches in the world, great for evening strolls, enjoying street food, and taking in the sea breeze.  Note: Swimming is not recommended due to strong currents.\n*   **Elliot's Beach (Besant Nagar Beach):** A cleaner and quieter beach than Marina, popular among families and younger crowds.\n*   **Covelong Beach (Kovalam Beach):** A picturesque beach known for its surfing spots and water sports activities. Located a bit outside the city.\n*   **MGM Dizzee World:** An amusement park located near the beach, great for families with kids.\n\n**Parks & Gardens:**\n\n*   **Semmozhi Poonga:** A botanical garden showcasing a variety of flora from around the world.\n*   **Arignar Anna Zoological Park (Vandalur Zoo):** One of the largest zoos in South Asia, housing a diverse collection of animals. Located a bit outside the city.\n*   **Guindy National Park:** A small national park located within the city, offering a glimpse of Chennai's natural biodiversity.\n*   **Huddleston Gardens of Theosophical Society:** Peaceful gardens within the Theosophical Society, offering a tranquil escape from the city's bustle.\n\n**Shopping & Entertainment:**\n\n*   **T. Nagar:** A bustling shopping district known for its textiles, jewelry, and electronics.\n*   **Pondy Bazaar:** Another popular shopping area offering a wide range of clothing, footwear, and accessories.\n*   **Express Avenue Mall:** A modern shopping mall with a variety of international and domestic brands, restaurants, and a multiplex cinema.\n*   **Phoenix Marketcity:** Another large mall with a wide selection of shops, dining options, and entertainment facilities.\n*   **Forum Vijaya Mall:** A popular mall in Vadapalani with a variety of stores, restaurants, and a multiplex.\n*   **Spencer Plaza:** One of the oldest shopping malls in India, featuring a mix of traditional and modern stores.\n\n**Other Notable Places:**\n\n*   **Madras War Cemetery:** A poignant reminder of World War II, where soldiers from various countries are laid to rest.\n*   **Birla Planetarium:** Offers fascinating insights into astronomy and space exploration.\n*   **Cholamandal Artists' Village:** An artist's commune showcasing contemporary art and sculptures. Located a bit outside the city.\n*   **Muttukadu Boat House:**  A scenic backwater area perfect for boating and enjoying the natural surroundings. Located a bit outside the city.\n\n**Tips for Planning Your Visit:**\n\n*   **Best Time to Visit:** The best time to visit Chennai is during the winter months (November to February) when the weather is relatively cooler and more pleasant.\n*   **Transportation:** Chennai has a well-developed public transportation system, including buses, trains, and metro. Taxis and auto-rickshaws are also readily available.  Consider using ride-sharing apps like Uber or Ola for convenience.\n*   **Accommodation:** Chennai offers a wide range of accommodation options, from budget-friendly guesthouses to luxury hotels.\n*   **Food:** Don't miss out on trying the local cuisine, including South Indian staples like idli, dosa, sambar, and rasam.  Explore local restaurants and street food stalls for an authentic experience.\n*   **Respect Local Customs:** Dress modestly when visiting religious sites and be mindful of local customs and traditions.\n\nTo help me give you more specific recommendations, tell me:\n\n*   **How long will you be in Chennai?**\n*   **What are your interests (history, culture, beaches, shopping, etc.)?**\n*   **What is your budget?**\n*   **Are you traveling with children?**\n\nEnjoy your trip to Chennai!\n",
